        <p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">An exponent refers
              to the number of times a number is multiplied by itself. For =
example,
              2 to the 3rd (written like this: 2<sup>3</sup>) means:</font>=
</p>
        <blockquote>
          <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>2 x 2 x 2 =
=3D 8</strong></font>.</p>
        </blockquote>
          <p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">2<sup>3</sup> is n=
ot the same as 2 x 3 =3D 6.</font>
        </p><p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Remember that a =
number raised to the power of 1 is itself. For example,</font>
</p><blockquote>
          <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>a<sup>1</sup=
> =3D a</strong></font></p>
          <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>5<sup>1</sup=
> =3D 5</strong></font>.</p>
</blockquote>

        <p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">There are some speci=
al cases:</font></p>
        <blockquote>
          <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>1. a<sup>0</=
sup> =3D 1</strong></font></p>
          <blockquote>
            <p></p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">When an expo=
nent is zero,
            as in 6<sup>0</sup>, the expression is always equal to 1.</font=
><p></p>
            <blockquote>
              <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>a<sup>0<=
/sup> =3D 1</strong></font></p>
              <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>6<sup>0<=
/sup> =3D 1</strong></font></p>
              <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>14,356<s=
up>0</sup> =3D 1</strong></font></p>
            </blockquote>
          </blockquote>
          <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>2. a<sup>-m<=
/sup> =3D 1 / a<sup>m</sup></strong></font></p>
          <blockquote>
            <p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">When an exponent=
 is a negative
                  number, the result is always a fraction. Fractions consis=
t of a numerator
                  over a denominator. In this instance, the numerator is al=
ways 1.
                  To find the denominator, pretend that the negative expone=
nt is positive,
                  and raise the number to that power, like this:</font></p>
            <blockquote>
              <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>a<sup>-m=
</sup> =3D 1 / a<sup>m</sup></strong></font></p>
			  <p><font face=3D"Courier New, Courier, mono"><strong>6<sup>-3</sup> =
=3D 1 / 6<sup>3</sup></strong></font></p>
            </blockquote>
          </blockquote>
        </blockquote>
        <p><font face=3D"Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">You can have
                  a variable to a given power, such as a<sup>3</sup>, which=
 would mean a x a x a.=20
				  You can also have a number to a variable power, such as
                  2<sup>m</sup>, which would mean 2 multiplied by itself m =
times. We will
        deal with that in a little while. </font></p>
        <p align=3D"right"><a href=3D"http://www.mclph.umn.edu/mathrefresh/=
exponents2.html"><img src=3D"http://www.mclph.umn.edu/mathrefresh/images/ri=
ght.gif" name=3D"to_next" width=3D"15" height=3D"15" border=3D"0" id=3D"to_=
